  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Selection of Remedy
  author: Hong Eon-joong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Long since I've seen the man of Zengshan mountain—
    through my window comes an early autumn chill.
    How sleek your sheep have grown, my friend,
    while my garden grows wild day by day.

    A neglected garden can be tended again,
    but this sickness deep in my vitals—how heal it?
    Three years I cannot endure,
    and eight long years, who could bear?

    Beset by such thoughts, sorrow overwhelms me;
    sometimes I cough up blood across my bed.
    My spirit wavers, lost in confusion—
    whether sitting or walking, I forget myself.
    My vital essence daily wastes away,
    and I grow rigid as a withered tree.

    The village paths are swept bare of footprints;
    who would venture to this forgotten corner?
    I hear tell of a purple foal,
    roaming wild in all directions, east and west—
    why does it never reach my door?
    When I dwell on this, I can only gaze upon the distant sea.

    I prepared a stern letter to send,
    calling for brush and ink close at hand,
    when suddenly my servant burst through,
    bringing words in familiar characters.
    Reading them brought comfort to my weary heart—
    and lo, of my lingering illness, nine parts in ten have fled!

    I see my servant off at the gate now;
    the sea churns white while green mountains recede far away.
  footnotes:
    - 'Zengshan: likely refers to a respected friend or hermit sage, whose absence marks the beginning of the speaker''s isolation and illness.'
    - The contrast between the friend's thriving sheep and the speaker's wild garden symbolizes the divergence between health and decline.
    - The 'purple foal' may represent a metaphorical messenger or blessing that the speaker feels has eluded him until the servant's arrival.
    - The numerical references (three years, eight years, nine parts) reflect traditional Chinese numerology and its association with completion and healing.
